{"text": "Light Bears is a cute and includes some swearing but adds to the quirky nature of the game. The entire premise of the game is like a fusion between tag and hide and seek and oddly enough, its every bit as fun as it was playing tag as a kid, as well as hide and seek. The game is very easy to learn, but oh so hard to properly master. Tutorial is quick and easy to complete, about 2-3 minutes and pretty simple/standard stuff to most fps games, just some minor mechanics you need to learn but nothing too complex. Essentially one player is a shadow and will work to corrupt the light bears into its helpful minions. The terrible puns and interesting humor of the devs further adds to the charm of this game. The premise is similar to other games of the survival horror genre, run and hide as a light bear, and even hide within objects which makes you invulnerable while you hide, but this isn't permanent and on a fixed timer. You can have a victory of shadow or light, either by infecting all bears as a shadow or by having all the bears escape into the light. So far, if a shadow plays smart, the game is heavily in their favor and almost impossible for a light victory said players are either well coordinated or know how to play the game well. There appears to be some rotation of the shadows for players who are f2p so they can use the different shadows as time progresses without actually having to buy the full game dlc, but cosmetics are almost entirely locked behind the dlc. The game is still immensely entertaining, running from the shadows and the shadow bears, as is chasing down your former comrades. The levels are sometimes hit or miss, some being very fun and complex to play in, others being extremely simple in design that it gives shadows a larger advantage than the usual corrupted bears. The game itself is not by any means pay to win, the only benefit of actually buying the dlc is the opportunity to fully customize your character in terms of color, cape, emote, music, and a far wider variety of hats, which are limited to 2 hats for f2p, and being able to use any of the shadows when you are the shadow, even if they are not currently in rotation. The game is quite recently released and the devs appear to be eager to add new things and hear feedback from its community. The community itself is generally quite positive and surprisingly not very toxic if at all, at least from my own games. Though the game is quite fun just jumping in and playing, the game is immensely far more enjoyable when played with your own friends, which is what I primarily experienced. Though playing on your own is fun as well, there is just something about having your friend be the shadow and having to survive against them that just playing solo canâ€™t replicate, at least not yet. As it is, the game looks quite promising but a seems to be lacking some content, at least on the f2p side. Most of the content(shadow selection wise and level wise) can be experienced within an hour or two or playing. Regardless, the experience is still one to at least try, as some people play this game quite passionately, I myself am barely around level 10 but I have seen people in the 30s and there are some likely higher. 6/10 If you enjoyed this review, please follow our curator", "appid": "765710", "steamid": "profiles/76561198199595411", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "104", "votes_funny": "5", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1540814400.0}
