{"text": "I have tried all 3 Witcher games now and I really want to like the game but it just keeps disappointing me. The first game  kept crashing on my system so I moved to Witcher 2. I put several hours into the game, mostly doing tutorials and watching cut scenes, then when you finally get around to playing its clunky combat system makes the missions unnecessarily difficult and sucks the fun out of them. Witcher 3 has a much better combat system but still tons of cut scenes. After playing for 2 hours I feel like I maybe got 20 minutes of actual gameplay. Then, I run over a hill, which turned out to be about an 8 foot drop, and my character fell and died. At this point all I could do was bust out laughing and turn off the game. Seriously, I could have survived this drop in real life and it killed a Witcher? Aren't they supposed to be super tough? Well apparently their legs are their weak point because if they trip over a tree root they're gonna die. I enjoyed the game enough to try it some more but if you are going to play the Witcher because everyone says how good of a game it is, don't get your hopes up to high unless you are easily impressed by fancy graphics and excellent story telling. In my opinion those are the real strong points of the game, the actual game mechanics have been flawed in every entry in the series. It's not a bad game just a bit frustrating, something that would definitely appeal more to a serious gamer, I would not recommend this for the casual player, I feel many hours need poured into this one to fully appreciate it.", "appid": "292030", "steamid": "profiles/76561198136350157", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1545912000.0}
