{"text": "Don't buy the season pass Full-Price, purchase it on a sale. To that note, I see that it's \"mostly\" negative but I don't think that's very fair, as it offers more, if not, the same amount of content as the Skyrim DLC and I believe that the workshop packs are at fault here...that or Bethesda's necessity to keep it at full price when not on sale..either or. Edit: Seems like this is popular enough to warrant a full review so here goes nothing: (In order of DLC Magnitude and worthiness) : 9/10 : Large : New World, Weapons, Armor, Perks, Enemies, Legendary Effects, \"Perk Tiers\", Companion (1) Far Harbor is what most fans would agree is \"Fallout 4 with better freedom of narrative\", and when I say that, It offers a vast amount of options over the base game such as dealing  on a versatile level with any faction you want, and even coming back to the one you \"sided\" with just to eliminate them and more than a handful of outcomes depending on your actions. The amount of freedom, choice, and exploration this dlc offers is leagues ahead of Fallout 4 \"to a point\", and at least justifies buying the Season Pass on sale just with the inclusion of this expansion alone. The biggest gripe with this \"expansion\" is how short the story is, and the utter dissapointment that was the   and could've easily  It's highly recommended to take Nick Valentine with you as it expands on his backstory. : 6.5/10 : Big : New World, Weapons, Armor, Perks, Enemies, Legendary Effects, Perk \"Tiers\", Companion (1) Or \"being evil in Fallout 4 for once\", Nuka World is a fairly big expansion with huge emphasis on new \"gimmicks\" such as Nuka Cola flavors, puzzles, attractions and \"some\" (and by that I mean exactly one) rollercoasters that you can ride along with various places in the park. The DLC's biggest downfall is not expanding on the various attractions that you can visit with most being broken down and being offered no option to \"fix\" them later on, rather, just turn on the parks power and enjoying what survived the apocalypse. The companion \"Gage\" could've been fleshed out more but is an alright companion for what we were given. Definitely doesn't justify the price by itself, but it's a nice extra world to explore if you pick up the pass. : 8.5/10 (if this was an original idea not done before it'd easily be a 9/10, refer to Rob Co. mod on nexusmods) : Small : New \"location\", robot companion creation station, new enemy faction, a few new weapons, a new armor set Automatron is actually pretty great for the price it's offered allowing to create your own robotic companions for settlements, to accompany you, and quite a bit of customization that's further expanded upon with mods. The story line didn't needed to be added in but it's a nice gimmick, taken aback by the fact that you can't hire a certain someone as a companion which is a real shame. Needless to say this idea isn't original, but it's a nice throwback to The Mechanist from Fallout 3 and you can easily invest hours into creating your own robotic army. Worth the 5 dollars, and a nice extra to go along with the Season Pass. : 6.5/10 : Small? Medium capabilities : A large assortment of new \"vault pieces\", the ability to build your own vault and new gimmicks to place in them. Certaintly the better of the \"workshop\" dlc's, Vault-Tec Workshop could have been expanded further by allowing you to build your own underground vaults at the plot of your choosing rather than one area on the map. It's cheap, not great by any regard but it opens up a lot of building opportunity if you enjoy th settlement system. : 3/10 : Very Small, Medium Capabilities : New \"contraption\" helping tools such as Gates (XOR, etc.) to help with distributing electricity, gadgets, and objects It's..alright, but should've been included as a free update, as should have been most of these to at least appease the fans a little and I believe it would've been better off if not for the price tag attached to it. As a DLC, however, the Gates and new additions are a great help as is the signs and labels, and neon but still feels like content that was \"cut\" out at the last moment, and is even shown in Vault 76 to give hint to it The score is completely dedicated to the new \"content\" it adds, and would've been an easy 7/10 if not for them selling it seperately. : 2/10 : New \"settler\" objects, Arena objects, Capturable creatures, Alarms and Traps, objects that already exist in-game and are converted to placeable objects *sigh* where to begin... Wasteland Workshop is a toss-up, but easily the worst workshop dlc of the bunch; where as it may add \"new\" things, it also recycles existing content and packages as sold content which is where it got its score from. It has some neat little gimmicks, some nice capability for arenas, and the concrete is really great..but looking at how they could've just released this as a free \"update\", or even a \"free dlc\", it severely knocks down the magnitude of this dlc and makes it extremely underwhelming. It's certaintly not worth purchasing by itself as compared to the other workshop packs, and is arguably the worst dlc that Bethesda has ever released for a game. Let's face it, at least Horse Armor was \"new\", and a joke...a really bad joke, but not as bad as this. Is the Season Pass worth it on a sale? for sure. Full price? It's your money, but if you want my opinion and considering how much of this could've been free...not even close.", "appid": "404090", "steamid": "profiles/76561198045143116", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "38", "votes_funny": "5", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1466683200.0}
