{"text": "Man, am I glad I stayed within the 2 hour mark so I could refund this game. First off, I gotta say, I had been looking forward to the release of Overgrowth for a long time. For as far as I can remember, I found it about... Five, maybe six years ago, and really liked the look of it. Now, after pretty much forgetting about it, and seeing posts about it every now and then - it's finally out! But, it's far from worth the price. The mechanics and combat of the game are truly fun for an hour or two, but you can get bored really quickly. (In my opinion.)  The story mode is... Eh. That's honestly the best word I have for it. It tries to throw weird mythology about the bunny-people, dog-people and their Gods and whatnot, but all I could find myself thinking during the 'cutscenes' (which are pretty much almost just stills with a weird angle) was: \"What the â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ is this?\" So, the first 10-20 minutes are pretty neat. Discovering the idea behind the game, and the mechanics of the combat system. This whole combat system immediately falls apart when you discover the bunny kick. You jump in the air, and launch both your bunny feet at the opponent. There's a chance this'll kill them in one go, and if it doesn't: Just do it again. No reason to use the other, now-clunky-looking combat options there are. I would not buy this game at the set price of 30 bucks, nor would I buy it at the promotion price of around 20 bucks. If you have some cash to spare, this might not be so bad- but after 9 years in development, this is what the team pushed out? This? No thank you.", "appid": "25000", "steamid": "profiles/76561198048064777", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1508241600.0}
