{"text": "Ok, let's talk about the obvious aspects about Halo CE:A first. This remaster actually reminds me a lot to those PC mods of older games where fans just take random assets from newer games or use realistic textures taken from other places in an attempt to make it look \"new\" or \"realistic\" but just ends up looking goofy. And this remaster does that a lot.  Textures taken from other games that look out of place together; models for props, vehicles and some weapons were taken directly from Halo Reach, and some other weapon models were taken from Halo 3 so both designs clash constantly. Like in the mission with the sniper rifle where it attempts to look realistic and gritty but then you look at your secondary weapon and is the shiny and plastic looking assault riffle from Halo 3.  The same happens with the characters, where all the marines were taken from Halo Reach so they all look dirty and rough, but then you have Cortana using the Halo 3 Model which looks out of place. And talking about clashing, they use the Halo 3 flood models for the combat form of Elites which looks nothing like Halo Reach/CE:A Elites so is pretty noticeable (as they also reused the white models by accident even tho Halo CE didn't have white elites), which is kinda weird concidering that for the marine floods they used the Halo 3 models as a base and then they modified the model to use the Halo Reach marine bits added to it. But to be honest I dont really mind all that as I appreciate what they were going for, specially knowing that the company that made this remaster (Saber Interactive) has nothing to do with Halo and that Microsoft only gave them a few months to make this remaster, so is a miracle that this wasn't a complete trainreck. The thing that I mind and that I really hate is actually the geometry of the models as NONE of them match at ALL the original geometry. Like, sometimes you want to shoot an enemy that is poping around a corner, tree, rock or mountain and the bullets just get stopped in midair like if the enemies had mind control, but if you change to classic graphics then nope, is just that the reused models for those props are way smaller and slimer in an attempt to make them look more realistic, but that just ends up confusing the player. Is specially annoying in the second mission where the enemies are surounded by trees that you always end up shooting because the Aniverssary models are a third of the original size, so you either switch to original graphics to see what's actually going on, or just straight up always fight in open areas without cover because otherwise you are going to get confused. Another negative but small point to mention is the framerate. For some bizarre reason when playing with Classic Graphics you will start to see constant stutters and framedrops that strangely enough never happen with Anniversary Graphics. No idea of what causes it but is pretty obvious they won't fix it. So are there any positive aspects about game? Actually yes, and is a big one. The multiplayer is flawless in this version and is by far the best way to play Halo CE in multiplayer. Finding matches doesn't take that long and the connection is just perfect, and way better than the GearBox port that was filled with horrible latency issues, which is odd concidering this is suposed to be that version. They also added multiplayer medals from the newer games and added challenges to unlock minimalistic weapon skins for the weapons and vehicles alongside being able to unlock different visor colors. And I love that if you are one of those purist who thinks that a golden Magnum Pistol or a white Scorpion Tank will ruin the game, you can just disable it as it is the first graphical option that pops up in Halo CE.  The only problem being that a server browser for custom matches like in the original port will not be a thing until a few months. If you really like the Halo CE's multiplayer then this buy is a no brainer. This version will give you the best experience in terms of connection, content, map selection and progression.  But if you don't really like the Anniversary graphics and don't really care about playing Halo CE's Multiplayer with acceptable latency, then just stick with the original port made by gearbox almost 20 years ago, as this version will not bring you anything. Not to mention that GearBox shared the full source code in a John Carmack style so that is safe to download without feeling like a pirate. PS: Don't even try to play the campaign co-op as even on LAN with cables connected directly between both computers you are going to suffer constant lag spikes which makes no sense. The same problem happens with Halo 3, but here is just even worse.", "appid": "1064221", "steamid": "profiles/76561198320261755", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "6", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1597147200.0}
