{"text": "Type: Technically a JRPG with lots of features. TL;DR: Not a bad game exactly, there just wasn't anything to pull me in or keep me interested. Would rate as neutral if steam allowed it. Pros: 1. There are actually multiple art styles in the game, but the ones that deserve praise are the in combat animations and the action selection drawings. The combat animations are smooth, unique, and really convey the character in motion. The selection drawings are a set of comic book style drawings for each and every action you can take. 2. Content, the game has loads of it. At 9 hours I had barely begun to scratch the surface of the game. 3. Mechanics:The game is mostly balanced between the heroes and the overcharge system while difficult to work with at first really starts to shine once you get some upgrades and skills. Neutrals: Out of combat animation and art: Kind of clunky and ill defined, but gets the job done. Crafting and inventory: While both are functional they could desperately use some quality of life improvements. Being able to craft multiples of the same item/not have to press and hold E for 3 seconds and the ability to just see all items per character instead of having to click into every slot are possible examples. Story: Nothing terrible, but nothing great. Pretty bland. Cons: Characters: The characters are all pretty much overused tropes. We have a broody, gruff, tough-guy veteran; energetic kid who wants to help their friends and everyone has kinda adopted; robot who was built for war, but is actually peaceful and loves nature, complete with bird entourage; wizard who is a grumpy old man; scantily clad \"sexy\" rogue lady who use pistols and bombs. Game flow: While the mechanics are great the game boils down to several hundred of the same battles over and over again. It was so grindy that after 9 hours I stopped.", "appid": "451020", "steamid": "profiles/76561198052829328", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false,